<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-624-902  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 624 902.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 25 1990 v4 n25 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army to lose most under DOD ADP consolidation. (Department ofDefense proposes merger of automatic data processing facilities )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Army did not propose many data processing installation(DPI) mergers when it submitted plans to the Department of Defense(DOD) Information Resources Management Dept (IRM) under the DOD'sautomatic data processing (ADP) consolidation plan.andP;  The IRM hassuggested incorporating the Army's planned $800 million SustainingBase Information System into the DOD merged ADP operations.andP;  TheNavy and the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) both draftedcomprehensive merger plans which were subsequently approved by theIRM.andP;  The Air Force proposed the merger of some DPIs and will bedirected to include centers operated by the Logistics Command.andO;The Army did not include merging any central design activities(CDAs) nor the computers used by its Materiel Command and severalother commands.andP;  The Navy's (and Marine's), DLA's and Air Force'splans and expected savings are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data ProcessingFacility ManagementReorganizationGovernment RegulationRequirements AnalysisUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. ArmyUnited States. NavyUnited States. Air Force.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>